[[File:Reappear_of_the_daimyo's_procession,_at_Akasaka,_Otowa.jpg|thumb|200x200px|Sugimori Hachimangu Shrine Festival]]
'''Shinko-shiki''' is a festival at [[Shinto shrine]]s where a divine spirit{{efn|The word "mikou" is based on the belief that a nobleman's outing would bring happiness, and the emperor's visit is called [[gyoko]], while the god's visit is called "jinko.<ref>World Encyclopedia, 2nd Edition, "Shinko Matsuri" (Heibonsha)</ref>。}} goes on a journey. It is also called '''Shinko-shiki'''. In most cases, the [[Shintai]] or [[Yorishiro]], in which the spirits of the gods reside, are transferred to a [[Mikoshi]], which then travels to the [[Ujigami]] community, or to the [[Otabisho]] or Moto-miya shrine. Most festivals featuring portable shrines and imperial carriages are considered to be a type of Shinko Matsuri.
In the broad sense, it refers to the entire go-kosai, while in the narrower sense, it refers to the outward journey from the shrine to the destination, such as an itinerary office. In a narrower sense, it refers to the outward journey from the shrine to the destination, such as a travel agency. In the latter case, the term "kankosai" is used for the outward journey from the destination to the shrine. In a broader sense, the term "Togyo-sai" also refers to the whole process of "Miyuki" (procession).

== Overview ==
The general significance of Shinko-sai is that it is an opportunity for the god of the birthplace to show his divine authority by touring the land of the Ujiko, and for the god and the Ujiko to mingle in close association.{{Sfn|Morita|2015|pp=41-51}} Although the rituals may be mixed, the form of the Shinkosai can be roughly divided into the following three categories according to the origin and character of the deity.{{Sfn|Morita|2015|pp=41-51}}

=== Gism type ===
A phenomenon seen in Ayazato and Yoshihama in Sanriku Town during the parade of portable shrines. The mysterious movement of the mikoshi is called gism mikoshi. When this happens, salt is sprinkled on the ground and the Gongen-sama tries to calm it down. This phenomenon is also thought to be caused by the will of God. (According to a person from the Ayazato district) The Ichikishimahime Shrine, the main shrine of the Nezumi district of Yoshihama, is an Ara-mikoshi.
In addition, in Yoshihama, Sanriku Town, [[mikoshi]] is said to be a violent one. The portable shrines of each shrine have four bells attached to the string (front and back together), which make a "jingling" sound when cruising and spin violently.
{{Sfn|Morita|2015|pp=41-51}}。

It is said that originally the divine spirit was welcomed at the [[Altar|Ritual]] in the village, but when the altar developed into a shrine, the act of welcoming remained as a "homecoming" with the opposite meaning, and became a Shinkosai. For this reason, the site of descent, such as a rock formation, became the go-tabisho, and today it is often the former shrine or the original site of the shrine{{Sfn|Morita|2015|pp=41-51}}。

