{{Short description|Religious ceremony}}
{{Draft topics|east-asia}}
{{AfC topic|other}}

<!-- Note: The following pages were redirects to [[Shinko-shiki]] before draftification:
*[[Jingu Sai]]
-->[[File:ToshoguMikoshi5.jpg|thumb|Shinko shiki for [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]] at {{Ill|Nikkō Tōshō-gū|en}}.]]
[[File:Miyamatsuri.JPG|thumb|Underwater shinko shiki at {{Ill|Yatsurugi Shrine|simple}}]]
Shinko-shiki (神幸式), also known as Shinko-sai (神幸祭) is a shinto ritual of moving the [[shintai]] of a [[kami]] in a procession<ref name=":02">https://archive.ph/UuQJU</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Hirayama |first=Miyuki |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KkIeAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Shinko-shiki&q=Shinko-shiki&hl=en |title=Matsuri in Shimomura: Experience, Performance, and History in a Japanese Festival |date=2001 |publisher=Indiana University |language=en}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=glIJAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Shinko-shiki&q=Shinko-shiki&hl=en |title=Basic Terms of Shinto |date=1958 |publisher=(The Association of Shinto Shriners) Kokugakuin University, Institute for Japanese Culture and Classics |language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book |last=Littleton |first=C. Scott |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=573YAAAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Shinko-shiki&q=Shinko-shiki&hl=en |title=Shinto: Origins, Rituals, Festivals, Spirits, Sacred Places |date=2002 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-521886-2 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Coogan |first=Michael David |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=888kAQAAIAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Shinko-shiki&q=Shinko-shiki&hl=en |title=Eastern Religions: Origins, Beliefs, Practices, Holy Texts, Sacred Places |last2=Narayanan |first2=Vasudha |date=2005 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-522190-9 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qFHVAAAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Shinko-shiki&q=Shinko-shiki&hl=en |title=Eastern Horizon |date=1964 |publisher=Eastern Horizon Press |language=en}}</ref>The Kami's [[shintai]] will be removed from the main [[Shinto shrine]] and be put in a {{Ill|Mikoshi|en}}, or a movable shrine.<ref name=":02" /><ref name=":12">{{Cite web |title=Shinkō-sai {{!}} Britannica |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Shinko-sai |access-date=2023-04-11 |website=www.britannica.com |language=en}}</ref> It usually takes place during an annual festival for a shrine<ref name=":12" /> The parade is considered a way for the kami to review and affirm the boundaries of a neighborhood or parish.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book |last=Ashkenazi |first=Michael |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RLCPn9QV4_UC&dq=shinko-shiki&pg=PA50 |title=Matsuri: Festivals of a Japanese Town |date=1993-03-01 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-1421-2 |language=en}}</ref>

There is high regional variation on how Shinko-shikis work.<ref name=":2" /> The most visible part of the parade is a group of marchers who walk or ride along a set route. The parades require organization and resources, and they are often organized as part of a shrine's ritual or related activities.<ref name=":2" />

The parades serve as affirmations of social boundaries because individuals and households contribute time and resources to their neighborhood or area's parade, participate in its organization or performance, and publicly display their membership through signs, posters, or jackets.<ref name=":2" />

This festival can take place on land or water, and the route and places visited are based on tradition. The festival can also include costumes and special rituals. It is sometimes called "O-watari" (お渡り) .<ref name=":02" />

The {{Ill|Gion Matsuri|en}} of {{Ill|Yasaka Shrine|en}} is a famous example of Shinko-sai.<ref name=":02" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=The Root of the Gion Matsuri: The Shinko Matsuri – EBISU恵比壽日藥直送 |url=https://ebisujapan.com/en/blogs/%E6%83%A0%E6%AF%94%E5%A3%BDblog/%E7%A5%87%E5%9C%92%E7%A5%AD%E7%9A%84%E6%A0%B9%E6%9C%AC-%E7%A5%9E%E5%B9%B8%E7%A5%AD |access-date=2023-05-21 |website=ebisujapan.com}}</ref>

Shinko Shiki is specifically associated with the visit of kami to its parishioners, but there is a wide range of performance and interpretation.<ref name=":2" />

For example Tokyo Shinko-shiki is rowdy and has lots of drinking, while in [[Yuzawa, Akita|Yuzawa]] it is quiet and formal.<ref name=":2" />

